{"term":"2013","caseName":"Madigan v. Levin","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2013/12-872","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - October 07, 2013","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/21758","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Our first case this term is Case 12-872, Madigan v. Levin.","start":0,"stop":7.254,"duration":7.25},{"text":"Mr. Scodro?","start":7.254,"stop":8.487,"duration":1.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":8.487,"stop":16.026,"duration":7.54},{"text":"Congress has crafted a comprehensive body of administrative and judicial procedures and remedies that are tailored specifically to combatting discrimination against older workers.","start":16.026,"stop":26.983,"duration":10.96},{"text":"In extending these procedures and remedies to government employees, Congress did not intend to permit State and municipal workers alone to frustrate this regime or bypass it entirely using the more general remedies of Section 1983.","start":26.983,"stop":43.193,"duration":16.21}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Scodro, there's a preliminary question before we get to the question you presented, and that is: What authority did the Seventh Circuit have to deal with the question under the Age Discrimination Act?","start":43.193,"stop":60.572,"duration":17.38},{"text":"I mean, it was -- it went to the Seventh Circuit on interlocutory review.","start":60.572,"stop":66.308,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":66.308,"stop":67.658,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"A qualified immunity question.","start":67.658,"stop":69.16,"duration":1.5},{"text":"Everybody agrees that there is no qualified immunity.","start":69.16,"stop":73.546,"duration":4.39},{"text":"That there -- that there is indeed a claim that the Equal Protection Clause includes age.","start":73.546,"stop":81.568,"duration":8.02},{"text":"So Second -- Seventh Circuit had no authority to deal with any question other than that, did it?","start":81.568,"stop":88.641,"duration":7.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It did, Your Honor.","start":88.641,"stop":90.108,"duration":1.47},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit properly followed this Court's holding in Wilkie.","start":90.108,"stop":94.043,"duration":3.94},{"text":"In Footnote -- in Footnote 4 of that opinion, the Court concluded correctly that whether or not there was a Bivens action for a recognized, in that case, due process violation, was itself part and parcel of the first prong of the qualified immunity inquiry and, therefore, properly considered on interlocutory--","start":94.043,"stop":111.587,"duration":17.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But in Wilkie, the whole case was dismissed by the district court, wasn't it?","start":111.587,"stop":115.458,"duration":3.87},{"text":"So whatever was said in that footnote was dicta.","start":115.458,"stop":121.195,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, there's an argument in one of the amicus briefs that the -- there was an alternative route under 1254 in Wilkie and -- and, therefore, the argument is raised that it was dicta.","start":121.195,"stop":133.77,"duration":12.58},{"text":"But it wasn't dicta in context, Your Honor.","start":133.77,"stop":136.122,"duration":2.35},{"text":"The court didn't consider that alternative route.","start":136.122,"stop":138.741,"duration":2.62},{"text":"The court squarely held that it had jurisdiction, and it goes on to say in the footnote that the appellate court properly exercised jurisdiction because the question of whether there is or is not a Bivens action for this constitutional right is properly considered part of the QI.","start":138.741,"stop":155.783,"duration":17.04}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we have an amicus brief from law professors who argue that the Seventh Circuit should not have considered the question of whether there was a cause of action under Section 1983.","start":155.783,"stop":169.624,"duration":13.84},{"text":"But they also go on to argue that we, nevertheless, have jurisdiction to consider that question, and that it is a -- a matter of discretion for us to decide whether to do that.","start":169.624,"stop":180.164,"duration":10.54},{"text":"Is that -- do you agree with that position?","start":180.164,"stop":181.548,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"We do agree with that position.","start":181.548,"stop":182.616,"duration":1.07},{"text":"They cite Clinton versus Jones and they cite the Fitzgerald decision for that position, Your Honor.","start":182.616,"stop":186.902,"duration":4.29},{"text":"And we would agree that while those may be modest extensions of the holdings in those cases, we would agree that this Court can exercise 2254 jurisdiction over the question.","start":186.902,"stop":195.258,"duration":8.36}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"If we adopt that formulation and that solution, is it as if we are granting certiorari before judgment on an issue in our own discretion?","start":195.258,"stop":204.697,"duration":9.44},{"text":"Is that the way it works?","start":204.697,"stop":205.647,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that -- no, I think the Court would still fairly consider the -- the Seventh Circuit's judgment on the issue, Your Honor.","start":205.647,"stop":213.153,"duration":7.51},{"text":"And, again, I would -- I would return to--","start":213.153,"stop":216.422,"duration":3.27}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But how -- what's the mechanism for us -- what's the rationale that we can exercise jurisdiction where a court of appeals could not?","start":216.422,"stop":224.61,"duration":8.19},{"text":"Because we have--","start":224.61,"stop":225.743,"duration":1.13}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well--","start":225.743,"stop":226.16,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--authority to grant certiorari before judgment or for some other reason?","start":226.16,"stop":230.431,"duration":4.27}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--The theory advanced in the amicus brief, with which we confer, that 1254 grants the Court jurisdiction over the case and that would include issues like this that were part and parcel of the case before the appellate court.","start":230.431,"stop":245.024,"duration":14.59},{"text":"Now, I should note that that amicus brief begins with the false premise that there was an exercise of pendent appellate jurisdiction in this case.","start":245.024,"stop":253.78,"duration":8.76},{"text":"And as we explained briefly in our reply brief, the one reference, the sole reference to pendent appellate jurisdiction on Page 7-A of the Petitioner's appendix is merely a reference or a brief description of the failed argument advanced by the Respondent that pendent jurisdiction would not be a proper proceeding here.","start":253.78,"stop":273.358,"duration":19.58},{"text":"And the Court did not advance.","start":273.358,"stop":274.291,"duration":0.93},{"text":"They squarely cited Wilkie and advanced along the--","start":274.291,"stop":278.343,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Could I go back, Mr. Scodro, to the -- to the rationale of -- of the -- that you're relying on.","start":278.343,"stop":286.016,"duration":7.67},{"text":"I mean, you keep on saying “ part and parcel ”.","start":286.016,"stop":288.368,"duration":2.35},{"text":"But how is it part and parcel?","start":288.368,"stop":290.668,"duration":2.3},{"text":"That seems to ally the distinction between a right and a remedy.","start":290.668,"stop":294.787,"duration":4.12},{"text":"There's one question whether there has been a violation of law.","start":294.787,"stop":297.906,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Sure.","start":297.906,"stop":298.173,"duration":0.27}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"There's another question whether a cause of action exists to remedy that violation.","start":298.173,"stop":302.625,"duration":4.45},{"text":"Why aren't those two separate inquiries?","start":302.625,"stop":305.16,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the Court in Wilkie moved from one to the other in the footnote.","start":305.16,"stop":310.131,"duration":4.97},{"text":"And I think that--","start":310.131,"stop":310.781,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I guess I'm asking you to explain it to me--","start":310.781,"stop":313.249,"duration":2.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Sure--","start":313.249,"stop":313.649,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--because that footnote is about a sentence long.","start":313.649,"stop":315.518,"duration":1.87},{"text":"So what's the theory as to why these are part and parcel of each other?","start":315.518,"stop":320.839,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Because a -- the Qualified Immunity Doctrine itself arises out of Section 1983 in Bivens, it would seem sensible as a matter of first principles to consider whether or not there is such a cause of action at all at the outset with the right to interlocutory appeal, rather than given the qualified immunity as defense from litigation is not just judgment.","start":320.839,"stop":343.702,"duration":22.86},{"text":"Rather than waiting until final judgment and on a 1291 appeal, then addressing for the first time on appeal.","start":343.702,"stop":349.772,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that seems a different argument, not that the two really are intertwined with each other, but it -- that it just might make sense to consider the one at the outset even though, in fact, it's a separate inquiry.","start":349.772,"stop":362.266,"duration":12.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I think -- and I want to be clear.","start":362.266,"stop":364.249,"duration":1.98},{"text":"I think there are two different rationales here.","start":364.249,"stop":366.115,"duration":1.87},{"text":"When discussing why Wilkie was correct in what it said in Footnote 4, I would submit my most recent answer, namely, that it's part and -- it is -- not part and parcel, but it is natural and rational to consider whether or not the cause of action exists at the outset.","start":366.115,"stop":384.161,"duration":18.05},{"text":"With regard to--","start":384.161,"stop":384.844,"duration":0.68}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you're correct that the two are one and the same, how -- how is it that we have authorized district courts to do the one or the other?","start":384.844,"stop":399.337,"duration":14.49},{"text":"We -- we have not required district courts to reach the merits if they're -- if they can resolve the question on the basis of qualified immunity alone.","start":399.337,"stop":410.559,"duration":11.22},{"text":"Well, how can that be?","start":410.559,"stop":412.328,"duration":1.77},{"text":"If the merits are necessarily part of the qualified immunity determination?","start":412.328,"stop":417.815,"duration":5.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, some of the merits we know are part of it under the Court's decision in Hartman where the Court concluded that the absence of the failure to properly plead an element is, indeed, properly considered a part of the qualified immunity inquiry.","start":417.815,"stop":431.808,"duration":13.99},{"text":"And here, the -- what Wilkie did essentially, as I read it, is essentially add to that line of cases the idea that the presence or not of the Bivens action in that case, but logically speaking, the Section 1983 action here would be -- would be appropriately considered as part of the -- the first prong of the traditional two-prong qualified immunity.","start":431.808,"stop":456.19,"duration":24.38}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"You're running up against the Seventh Circuit in that respect because the Seventh Circuit held that the existence of an -- whether ADEA was the exclusive remedy, that that was irrelevant to the qualified immunity issue.","start":456.19,"stop":473.219,"duration":17.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, toward the end of the Court's opinion, it's true, the Court uses the phrase that","start":473.219,"stop":480.156,"duration":6.94},{"text":"\"it's irrelevant to the qualified immunity inquiry. \"","start":480.156,"stop":482.341,"duration":2.19},{"text":"In that context, I would submit the Court is using the phrase “ qualified immunity ”, and I think this is clear in context, to refer as -- as lower courts have at times done to the second prong; that is, the clearly established element of qualified immunity.","start":482.341,"stop":498.534,"duration":16.19},{"text":"Earlier in the opinion, in the section labeled “ jurisdiction ”, the Court actually cites Wilkie and makes clear that it's following Wilkie's command that the presence or not of the Section 1983 action for recognized constitutional right is considered part of the first prong.","start":498.534,"stop":515.729,"duration":17.2}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If the existence of a cause of action could not be considered in an interlocutory qualified immunity appeal, what would the effect be on the defendant's right not to be tried, which is the whole reason for allowing an interlocutory appeal in qualified immunity cases?","start":515.729,"stop":533.273,"duration":17.54},{"text":"Wouldn't it be the case that if the district court found that there was no qualified immunity, then the case would have to be tried.","start":533.273,"stop":541.213,"duration":7.94},{"text":"And only at the end of the case could it be determined whether there actually was a cause of action.","start":541.213,"stop":547.533,"duration":6.32},{"text":"So you have a trial potentially about nothing.","start":547.533,"stop":550.152,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":550.152,"stop":551.402,"duration":1.25},{"text":"In my earlier response to Justice Sotomayor's question, I think there -- or Justice Kagan's question -- I apologize -- I think it was -- that's exactly right.","start":551.402,"stop":562.543,"duration":11.14},{"text":"This is immunity from litigation, immunity from suit.","start":562.543,"stop":565.662,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"The decision was that there was no qualified immunity.","start":565.662,"stop":568.713,"duration":3.05},{"text":"And the question is: Having determined there was no qualified immunity, should they have stopped there?","start":568.713,"stop":574.184,"duration":5.47},{"text":"There wouldn't have been a trial -- if there is no qualified immunity and they have no exemption from trial.","start":574.184,"stop":581.338,"duration":7.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":581.338,"stop":583.206,"duration":1.87},{"text":"To decide that there isn't qualified immunity, the Court needs to consider both prongs and resolve them both adverse to the defendant.","start":583.206,"stop":590.21,"duration":7},{"text":"And therefore, it was essential for the Court here to consider the argument that there is no Section 1983 action.","start":590.21,"stop":598.383,"duration":8.17}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure you see the distinction or -- or you're facing the distinction.","start":598.383,"stop":602.937,"duration":4.55},{"text":"The right not to be tried is one of qualified immunity.","start":602.937,"stop":606.306,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Correct.","start":606.306,"stop":607.306,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"But you can have a constitutional violation and still not have a remedy, which is what this question involves.","start":607.306,"stop":614.91,"duration":7.6},{"text":"So, how do we deal with the concept that other people who have motions to dismiss that are denied still undergo trials, still experience the expense, and yet we've said repeatedly, an interlocutory appeal is not warranted.","start":614.91,"stop":637.425,"duration":22.51},{"text":"And so, what makes it warranted here where a Court has already said that there was a -- or at least there's enough evidence to suggest a constitutional violation and that a reasonable officer wouldn't have believed his or -- a person would have believed his or her conduct was appropriate?","start":637.425,"stop":657.239,"duration":19.81}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, with regard to that question, I would return to the notion that is a matter of first principles, given that qualified immunity is an outgrowth of Section 1983.","start":657.239,"stop":669.062,"duration":11.82},{"text":"The Court was very just -- was justified in Wilkie in treating the presence or not of the cause of action.","start":669.062,"stop":676.999,"duration":7.94},{"text":"This is a -- we're not talking about an affirmative defense, for example, in the form of statute of limitations as one example.","start":676.999,"stop":685.172,"duration":8.17},{"text":"We're talking about the existence or not of the Bivens right in that case, in the Section 1983 right here.","start":685.172,"stop":692.677,"duration":7.5},{"text":"It seems consistent with the fact that qualified immunity exists as a defense against Section 1983 and Bivens to contemplate the existence or not of that cause of action right at the threshold.","start":692.677,"stop":707.52,"duration":14.84}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Maybe -- maybe you better say a few words about the merits?","start":707.52,"stop":711.489,"duration":3.97}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Your Honor.","start":711.489,"stop":712.355,"duration":0.87},{"text":"The ADEA's remedial regime has the two elements that this Court has looked at repeatedly in determining whether a comprehensive regime or a regime is sufficiently comprehensive to displace more general Section 1983.","start":712.355,"stop":730.217,"duration":17.86}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"There's another preliminary question, and that is, why are we talking about the ADEA when the district court held that the ADEA doesn't cover Mr. Levin.","start":730.217,"stop":741.858,"duration":11.64},{"text":"And there seems to be not much of a dispute about that.","start":741.858,"stop":747.412,"duration":5.55},{"text":"You're not arguing that the ADEA does cover him, are you?","start":747.412,"stop":752.066,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we are -- we are arguing that the ADEA's rights and remedies do apply to Mr. Levin.","start":752.066,"stop":757.368,"duration":5.3},{"text":"And the reason is that in 1991, with the amendments as part of the Civil Rights Overhaul Act that year, the amendments in that act extended, and it's a section entitled","start":757.368,"stop":768.742,"duration":11.37},{"text":"\"Coverage of previously exempt State employees. \"","start":768.742,"stop":771.544,"duration":2.8},{"text":"It -- it extended ADEA rights and remedies to the previously exempt policymakers at other high levels.","start":771.544,"stop":778.866,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Has the Court ever held that an antidiscrimination statute that does not provide any rights for a particular class of plaintiffs nevertheless extinguishes the right of action that those plaintiffs would have under Section 1983?","start":778.866,"stop":793.54,"duration":14.67},{"text":"What if Mr. Levin were under 40 years old?","start":793.54,"stop":796.109,"duration":2.57},{"text":"Would you say that his equal protection Section 1983 cause of action was extinguished by the ADEA?","start":796.109,"stop":802.647,"duration":6.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, we would not, Your Honor.","start":802.647,"stop":803.681,"duration":1.03},{"text":"And the reason--","start":803.681,"stop":805.683,"duration":2}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So what is the difference between someone who's under 40 and someone who is not an employee within the meaning of the ADEA?","start":805.683,"stop":812.687,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Sure.","start":812.687,"stop":813.27,"duration":0.58},{"text":"And again, we're talking about the 1974 to 1991 period, just to be clear, because since '91 appointees and employees alike are -- have the full range of ADEA rights and remedies.","start":813.27,"stop":824.492,"duration":11.22},{"text":"During that period, under 40s, as this Court held in Cline, that workers under the age of 40 simply were not part of the social ill that Congress aimed to redress.","start":824.492,"stop":837.901,"duration":13.41},{"text":"They were concerned with the plight of the relatively older worker.","start":837.901,"stop":841.52,"duration":3.62},{"text":"It's why the Court concluded in Cline that reverse discrimination is not covered and also the explanation for why Congress drew a line at age 40.","start":841.52,"stop":849.793,"duration":8.27},{"text":"Just as in Smith, for example, the Education of the Handicapped Act didn't extend to cover all manner of hurdles confronted by a disabled student, it -- it focused solely on a singular issue facing, a curricular issue facing these students.","start":849.793,"stop":866.405,"duration":16.61},{"text":"Undoubtedly, those students not covered by it would have retained their Section 1983 right.","start":866.405,"stop":872.809,"duration":6.4},{"text":"Same with under-40 here.","start":872.809,"stop":874.741,"duration":1.93},{"text":"Now, as to the -- the narrow exception that existed between '74 and '91 for high-level government policymakers, we have the EEOC's understanding of why exactly Congress did that.","start":874.741,"stop":887.318,"duration":12.58},{"text":"They did so because there was concern on the part of members of Congress that it would be inappropriate from a matter of federalism and operationally to have Federal involvement in the hiring decisions made by the highest members, the elected members of State and local government.","start":887.318,"stop":904.361,"duration":17.04},{"text":"And that concern applies equally to Section 1983 claims.","start":904.361,"stop":909.932,"duration":5.57},{"text":"Because that concern applies equally -- we're not talking about people who weren't within the scope of the social ill; we're talking about a deliberate carveout for reasons that apply equally to Section 1983 -- we would submit that the exception likewise would have had force during that interim period.","start":909.932,"stop":925.374,"duration":15.44}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"For some -- please.","start":925.374,"stop":926.926,"duration":1.55}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, why should we consider that question?","start":926.926,"stop":929.376,"duration":2.45},{"text":"If this -- if we were back in the era before the enactment of the GERA, yes, we would have to consider that question.","start":929.376,"stop":936.882,"duration":7.51},{"text":"But now that the new statute has been passed, why should we consider whether someone who was a non-employee lacked a -- a 1983 cause of action during the period when that -- prior to the enactment of that statute?","start":936.882,"stop":950.875,"duration":13.99}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You're actually -- absolutely correct, Your Honor.","start":950.875,"stop":953.142,"duration":2.27},{"text":"As we say in our reply brief, there is no need for the Court to confront that question in this case.","start":953.142,"stop":957.961,"duration":4.82}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Which question?","start":957.961,"stop":958.678,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"The question of whether or not between 1974 and 1991 exempt employees, those who then obtained ADEA rights in 1991, whether those employees could be -- their Section 1983 claims could have been displaced by -- notwithstanding the fact that they were carved out.","start":958.678,"stop":976.69,"duration":18.01}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But I think the point here is that Mr. Levin is covered not by the ADEA, but by a separate statute, the GERA.","start":976.69,"stop":984.696,"duration":8.01},{"text":"And there's a separate question whether the GERA would displace constitutional relief, which apparently has -- has never been argued to anybody in this case.","start":984.696,"stop":996.071,"duration":11.38}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Two points, Your Honor.","start":996.071,"stop":998.022,"duration":1.95},{"text":"First, as we explain in reply and in our opening brief, the GERA is properly considered merely a part of the broader remedial regime under the ADEA.","start":998.022,"stop":1011.513,"duration":13.49},{"text":"And we explain why to look at it otherwise would create all sort of manner of artificialities.","start":1011.513,"stop":1016.917,"duration":5.4},{"text":"It's -- it's -- we know from past statutes like the Genetics Act that was passed more recently the way in which Congress would incorporate GERA by reference instead of vice versa.","start":1016.917,"stop":1028.392,"duration":11.48},{"text":"We know that, for example, in that same 1991 Act, 1981(a) was added and provided punitive damages for a whole array of--","start":1028.392,"stop":1037.998,"duration":9.61}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there are some many similarities, many similarities, between the ADEA and the GERA.","start":1037.998,"stop":1043.5,"duration":5.5},{"text":"But there are also real differences.","start":1043.5,"stop":1044.902,"duration":1.4},{"text":"I mean, they're obvious -- they obviously cover different people; there are different procedural prerequisites for the suit; you get a different kind of review, you only get administrative review under the GERA.","start":1044.902,"stop":1056.743,"duration":11.84},{"text":"So it's a separate inquiry as to whether this statute that has some commonalities, some differences, displaces constitutional claims, and it's an inquiry that really has never been addressed in this case.","start":1056.743,"stop":1069.234,"duration":12.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--And, Your Honor, to the extent, if the Court has concerns about addressing that -- and again, I -- I'm happy to go on as to why it would be artificial to consider the two separately.","start":1069.234,"stop":1080.441,"duration":11.21},{"text":"But if the Court were to conclude that, rather than effectively amending the ADEA, that the GERA amendments in 1991 really created a whole new statute that needs to be considered independent, the proper remedy would not be to dismiss this appeal, but would be to vacate the Seventh Circuit's judgment to permit Respondent to raise a claim that is new to this case on the merits here; namely, that there are different rules for appointees than employees.","start":1080.441,"stop":1110.728,"duration":30.29}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"This is an -- the qualified immunity question is presented on interlocutory appeal.","start":1110.728,"stop":1115.196,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It is, Your Honor.","start":1115.196,"stop":1115.663,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Decisions on the merits, factual and legal, are still pending.","start":1115.663,"stop":1119.833,"duration":4.17},{"text":"Now, we have a determination by the district court that Mr. Levin is not an employee.","start":1119.833,"stop":1125.92,"duration":6.09}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1125.92,"stop":1126.653,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The prior district court determined that he was.","start":1126.653,"stop":1128.605,"duration":1.95},{"text":"The Respondent's alleged that he was an employee in their complaint.","start":1128.605,"stop":1132.224,"duration":3.62},{"text":"I presume, depending on how we rule on the qualified immunity issue, the parties may want to revisit their positions on that question as the case goes go forward.","start":1132.224,"stop":1139.913,"duration":7.69},{"text":"And the district court in the first instance, I suppose, would be the one to decide whether they're allowed to revisit the issue in light of the change in his perception of the law or not.","start":1139.913,"stop":1150.453,"duration":10.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":1150.453,"stop":1152.571,"duration":2.12},{"text":"If this -- if I'm understanding your question, that if -- if the -- depending on how this Court rules, it is always true under Rule 54 that he could seek to have the district court reconsider his status.","start":1152.571,"stop":1164.112,"duration":11.54},{"text":"It's also true that if he wished to proceed under the GERA process for vindicating ADEA rights, he has the option of seeking a dismissal without prejudice of his statutory claims -- this has occurred in a handful of district court opinions -- and then ask the EEOC if he can proceed in the first instance before an ALJ and to advance those claims.","start":1164.112,"stop":1187.711,"duration":23.6},{"text":"That is also an option.","start":1187.711,"stop":1188.661,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"But there are a few things I -- I don't really know.","start":1188.661,"stop":1191.013,"duration":2.35},{"text":"I mean, does -- do you have to allege a claim under GERA for this particular individual?","start":1191.013,"stop":1250.8,"duration":59.79},{"text":"I don't know.","start":1250.8,"stop":1198.768,"duration":-52.03},{"text":"And if you do, I don't know whether GERA simply picked up whatever saving of the equal protection otherwise would have existed in the ADEA or didn't.","start":1198.768,"stop":1211.509,"duration":12.74},{"text":"And I believe that GERA applies to employment discrimination claims based on gender or race or other things, right?","start":1211.509,"stop":1220.865,"duration":9.36},{"text":"Well, every circuit in the country has said you don't lose your -- your constitutional claim there.","start":1220.865,"stop":1229.302,"duration":8.44},{"text":"So are we supposed to read GERA, it goes this way in some cases and that way in other cases, when GERA is silent on the matter?","start":1229.302,"stop":1236.725,"duration":7.42},{"text":"And so I looked to see what the Seventh Circuit said.","start":1236.725,"stop":1243.728,"duration":7},{"text":"Nothing.","start":1243.728,"stop":1240.86,"duration":-2.87},{"text":"I looked to see what you argued below.","start":1240.86,"stop":1244.813,"duration":3.95},{"text":"I looked to see whether it's obvious that GERA does apply or doesn't apply and simply picks it up or not.","start":1244.813,"stop":1252.25,"duration":7.44},{"text":"Maybe I'm just being thick.","start":1252.25,"stop":1254.519,"duration":2.27},{"text":"But nonetheless, where I don't know so much and the whole case turns on it, why are we hearing an issue that might not even be in the case?","start":1254.519,"stop":1262.858,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the Seventh Circuit was -- pronounced a rule that was indifferent as between appointees and employees.","start":1262.858,"stop":1271.981,"duration":9.12},{"text":"The reason for that was the Seventh Circuit was asked to announce a rule that is indifferent as to employees and appointees.","start":1271.981,"stop":1278.635,"duration":6.65},{"text":"There was -- the Respondent sought and obtained a rule that the ADEA does not displace, period.","start":1278.635,"stop":1284.638,"duration":6}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's about people not like the client who's at issue here.","start":1284.638,"stop":1288.759,"duration":4.12},{"text":"That is about people whom the ADEA did cover.","start":1288.759,"stop":1292.477,"duration":3.72},{"text":"Isn't that an advisory opinion in respect to this case?","start":1292.477,"stop":1295.746,"duration":3.27},{"text":"I don't know.","start":1295.746,"stop":1296.313,"duration":0.57},{"text":"That has a certain ring to it.","start":1296.313,"stop":1297.615,"duration":1.3},{"text":"But -- but what are we doing, deciding whether the ADEA applies and in what way to a person to whom it doesn't apply, assuming that GERA is in fact a separate statute that you have to sue under, the answer to which I do not know and which has never been argued.","start":1297.615,"stop":1315.593,"duration":17.98}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, there's very little lower court authority on the effect of GERA.","start":1315.593,"stop":1321.231,"duration":5.64},{"text":"I will say that what courts have done for I -- there is a case, for example, in which the allegation was Title VII as amended in 1991.","start":1321.231,"stop":1329.334,"duration":8.1},{"text":"And the Court construed that naturally to include the GERA rights.","start":1329.334,"stop":1333.121,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And so if there's so little about it, sometime on occasion we dismiss a case as improvidently granted, which is not a particularly desirable thing to do.","start":1333.121,"stop":1343.244,"duration":10.12},{"text":"But how could we avoid doing that here?","start":1343.244,"stop":1345.612,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, to reiterate a point made just a few moments ago, I think that the proper resolution, if -- GERA and the ADEA, again, are really one remedial regime.","start":1345.612,"stop":1361.122,"duration":15.51},{"text":"And -- and I've -- I've pointed out 1981(a) as an example of a -- of a similar regime where punitive damages were added to a numbers of statutes.","start":1361.122,"stop":1369.061,"duration":7.94},{"text":"And yet if we considered any one of those statute today, we would agree that it includes punitive damages, even though it was added in a freestanding statute as part of the 1991 Act.","start":1369.061,"stop":1379.083,"duration":10.02},{"text":"But, again, I would say as a procedural matter, should the Court harbor concerns about this issue and wish to permit the claim that appointees and employees are entitled to different displacement rules and the counterargument that, no, they're not because GERA effectively amends and adds to the ADEA, the way to handle that procedurally would be to vacate the judgment below and to let the parties argue those points to that court.","start":1379.083,"stop":1407.852,"duration":28.77},{"text":"As it stands, the Seventh Circuit was asked to issue a broad pronouncement that is indifferent to whether -- the Seventh Circuit was well aware and states that Mr. Levin was subject to an interlocutory determination that he was an appointee.","start":1407.852,"stop":1422.596,"duration":14.74},{"text":"And the court went on, and the only relevance that had in the court's analysis based on the way it was framed below is that, well, because appointees and people under 40 and other categories appear to be carved out -- and we have answers to all of those in our briefs in response -- but because all of them appear to be carved out, the ADEA does not displace ever as to appointees or employees.","start":1422.596,"stop":1448.011,"duration":25.41},{"text":"That doesn't contemplate a new argument that as an -- as an appointee, rather, Mr. Levin has -- is subject to a different displacement rule.","start":1448.011,"stop":1456.615,"duration":8.6},{"text":"It would be for the Seventh Circuit to confront that in the first place.","start":1456.615,"stop":1458.815,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":1458.815,"stop":1459.415,"duration":0.6},{"text":"I -- the only issue that's before us is whether someone who's exempted from the ADEA still has a 1983 claim, correct?","start":1459.415,"stop":1471.791,"duration":12.38},{"text":"That's what the Seventh Circuit said.","start":1471.791,"stop":1473.458,"duration":1.67},{"text":"If you're not a part of the statute, then you still have your 1983 rights?","start":1473.458,"stop":1478.794,"duration":5.34}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, what the Seventh Circuit held is that the ADEA does not displace Section 1983 claims for employees or appointees.","start":1478.794,"stop":1491.186,"duration":12.39},{"text":"It was a sweeping ruling that was sought.","start":1491.186,"stop":1493.802,"duration":2.62},{"text":"And the contention now is, well, perhaps the court should not have reached such a sweeping ruling.","start":1493.802,"stop":1498.94,"duration":5.14},{"text":"Perhaps the court could have ruled instead that as an appointee, Mr. Levin is entitled to a different rule that is specific to appointees because they're exempt under the ADEA.","start":1498.94,"stop":1510.998,"duration":12.06},{"text":"That argument was never advanced before the Seventh Circuit.","start":1510.998,"stop":1514.45,"duration":3.45},{"text":"And at this point, again, we would say should the Court harbor concerns about addressing this case, we would ask that they -- they vacate and let the Seventh Circuit addressed that issue in the first instance.","start":1514.45,"stop":1526.441,"duration":11.99},{"text":"If permitted, I would like to reserve my remaining time for rebuttal.","start":1526.441,"stop":1529.141,"duration":2.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":1529.141,"stop":1529.559,"duration":0.42},{"text":"Mr. Theobald?","start":1529.559,"stop":1536.647,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1536.647,"stop":1540.532,"duration":3.88},{"text":"I'd like to first address the jurisdictional issue.","start":1540.532,"stop":1544.736,"duration":4.2},{"text":"We made the argument before the Seventh Circuit that the Seventh Circuit did not have jurisdiction to -- on this issue of preclusion.","start":1544.736,"stop":1555.374,"duration":10.64},{"text":"And we argued that under Swint, the Court's decision in Swint, on an interlocutory appeal of qualified immunity, the Court would have to reach the -- in order to reach the issue of qualified immunity, it would have to address the preclusion issue.","start":1555.374,"stop":1573.253,"duration":17.88},{"text":"And our position was you don't have to look at -- you don't even consider that on qualified immunity.","start":1573.253,"stop":1581.776,"duration":8.52},{"text":"It's not part of the equation.","start":1581.776,"stop":1583.128,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we said the exact opposite in Wilkie in Footnote 4.","start":1583.128,"stop":1587.163,"duration":4.04},{"text":"I mean, you can say it's only a footnote, but it is what we said.","start":1587.163,"stop":1589.881,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we respectfully disagree, Your Honor.","start":1589.881,"stop":1592.983,"duration":3.1},{"text":"And we made that argument and in the decision that the Seventh Circuit reached they said: We didn't have to consider this preclusion issue to reach the qualified immunity denial, that qualified immunity was not applicable.","start":1592.983,"stop":1608.509,"duration":15.53},{"text":"So we did argue that and that was our position there.","start":1608.509,"stop":1613.997,"duration":5.49},{"text":"With respect to the issue presented here, the only thing that is pertinent is whether or not the ADEA can preclude an individual who's not covered by it, regardless if that individual is under 40 years old or if they're exempt from the statute or if they have a claim that the ADEA doesn't address.","start":1613.997,"stop":1637.695,"duration":23.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, your brother--","start":1637.695,"stop":1638.861,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But did--","start":1638.861,"stop":1639.311,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--who just sat down explained that the Seventh Circuit's ruling didn't consider the issue that you're -- you're talking about now.","start":1639.311,"stop":1647.234,"duration":7.92}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I would respectfully disagree, Your Honor.","start":1647.234,"stop":1650.003,"duration":2.77},{"text":"We -- the Seventh Circuit -- we made it clear in the Seventh Circuit that Mr. Levin had been excluded.","start":1650.003,"stop":1658.608,"duration":8.61},{"text":"He was excluded in July of 2011 by a decision of District Court Chang.","start":1658.608,"stop":1663.926,"duration":5.32},{"text":"He said in that--","start":1663.926,"stop":1665.278,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Was that the -- was that the first one or the second one?","start":1665.278,"stop":1667.214,"duration":1.94}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--The second one.","start":1667.214,"stop":1667.68,"duration":0.47},{"text":"Judge Korr initially decided the issue twice and said Mr. Levin was covered by the ADEA.","start":1667.68,"stop":1673.784,"duration":6.1}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In your brief, could I just -- you say -- I think this is pretty close to the exact words: There's no realistic possibility of your obtaining a holding that Mr. Levin is an employee within the ADEA.","start":1673.784,"stop":1688.561,"duration":14.78},{"text":"But do you concede that now?","start":1688.561,"stop":1689.994,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"I concede that there's no realistic possibility.","start":1689.994,"stop":1692.777,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1692.777,"stop":1693.129,"duration":0.35},{"text":"Do you concede that he is not an employee?","start":1693.129,"stop":1695.029,"duration":1.9},{"text":"If you just say that there's no realistic possibility that the courts are going to take this correct position, then the issue is still in the case.","start":1695.029,"stop":1702.485,"duration":7.46},{"text":"So is it your position that he is an employee or he is not an employee?","start":1702.485,"stop":1706.77,"duration":4.29}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I -- I mean, they dodged -- he's -- the court has ruled, the Seventh Circuit in Opp v. Cook County State's Attorney, Your Honor, made it very clear their State's attorneys would be -- appointees would not be covered under the ADEA.","start":1706.77,"stop":1724.315,"duration":17.55}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you're not willing to say that he is not an employee, then the issue is still in the case, and we would have -- if we were to rule on the ADEA issue, wouldn't we have to decide whether there is a remedy for somebody who is an employee within the ADEA?","start":1724.315,"stop":1744.745,"duration":20.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1744.745,"stop":1745.745,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The district court might be wrong on that.","start":1745.745,"stop":1747.597,"duration":1.85},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit might be wrong on that.","start":1747.597,"stop":1749.365,"duration":1.77},{"text":"And you may be right.","start":1749.365,"stop":1750.715,"duration":1.35},{"text":"There's not much of a realistic possibility that you're going to get a reversal of that.","start":1750.715,"stop":1754.333,"duration":3.62},{"text":"But the issue is still in the case unless you want to give it up.","start":1754.333,"stop":1756.869,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the Court will so rule.","start":1756.869,"stop":1760.587,"duration":3.72},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit ruled in the Opp v. Cook County case and this Court denied cert in 2011 on the Opp v. Cook County case.","start":1760.587,"stop":1769.777,"duration":9.19},{"text":"But to stand here--","start":1769.777,"stop":1771.043,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So you don't want to -- you don't want to give it up, which makes sense.","start":1771.043,"stop":1772.812,"duration":1.77},{"text":"I mean, you've got a client.","start":1772.812,"stop":1773.912,"duration":1.1},{"text":"It depends on what we do, right?","start":1773.912,"stop":1775.931,"duration":2.02},{"text":"I mean, depending on what our ruling is, it may be advantageous to you to argue, as you alleged in your complaint, that he's an employee.","start":1775.931,"stop":1783.368,"duration":7.44}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, as we stand here now, he is not in this case.","start":1783.368,"stop":1788.155,"duration":4.79},{"text":"And I -- I don't know--","start":1788.155,"stop":1790.873,"duration":2.72}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"It's pretty universal he's not an employee under ADEA, though he might be under GERA.","start":1790.873,"stop":1795.925,"duration":5.05},{"text":"You have to say yes or no, because if you're going to say -- I mean, you know, let's either do it or not do it.","start":1795.925,"stop":1803.864,"duration":7.94},{"text":"If you -- if you want to leave this issue in the case, it's possible to argue we should decide this whole issue on the ground that although he's not really a bird, he's a fish or whatever.","start":1803.864,"stop":1815.422,"duration":11.56},{"text":"But I mean, this is supposed to be fairly realistic, I think, what we're supposed to do.","start":1815.422,"stop":1820.31,"duration":4.89}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Okay.","start":1820.31,"stop":1821.176,"duration":0.87},{"text":"Well, going back to Mr. Levin being not covered, we believe the Court's decision in Davis v. Passman and the Court's decision in Smith v. Robinson, which is the only case where the Court has precluded a 1983 constitutional claim, that that--","start":1821.176,"stop":1840.789,"duration":19.61}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, just to get this clear, you asked for this ruling from the Seventh Circuit.","start":1840.789,"stop":1847.793,"duration":7},{"text":"And -- and you won based on a factual record that was no different then than it is now.","start":1847.793,"stop":1854.197,"duration":6.4},{"text":"You asked for this ruling based on these facts, you won, and now you want to insulate that from the new review.","start":1854.197,"stop":1861.967,"duration":7.77},{"text":"I mean, I think it'd -- it'd be a feather in your cap if you can pull it off.","start":1861.967,"stop":1867.605,"duration":5.64},{"text":"But it seems to me -- it seems to me that since you asked for the ruling on the merits and got it, we ought to be able to review it to determine whether it's right or wrong.","start":1867.605,"stop":1877.895,"duration":10.29},{"text":"And to the extent there's a factual issue that would persist in the case if it goes back on qualified immunity, you and the parties can reposition themselves on that.","start":1877.895,"stop":1887.934,"duration":10.04},{"text":"I mean, it is an issue that was apparently close enough for one district court to say yes, the other district court, on looking at it again, to say no.","start":1887.934,"stop":1894.505,"duration":6.57},{"text":"The deck will be reshuffled depending on how we rule.","start":1894.505,"stop":1898.407,"duration":3.9},{"text":"And as I see you standing there, I don't see you willing to concede for -- for the future that he's not an employee.","start":1898.407,"stop":1904.211,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, we think the difference was after the district court's decision in our case, that the Seventh Circuit decided another case in 2010.","start":1904.211,"stop":1915.086,"duration":10.88},{"text":"And that's why the second district court judge followed that precedent.","start":1915.086,"stop":1920.239,"duration":5.15},{"text":"And that precedent, where this Court denied cert, there's no real possibility that any court is going to find Mr. Levin as being covered by the ADEA.","start":1920.239,"stop":1931.28,"duration":11.04}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"There's no real possibility that any court is going to find that your client was, in fact, an employee without GERA.","start":1931.28,"stop":1938.551,"duration":7.27},{"text":"That's what you said; is that right?","start":1938.551,"stop":1940.986,"duration":2.44}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"GERA is -- is another--","start":1940.986,"stop":1944.038,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"It's a different statute.","start":1944.038,"stop":1945.038,"duration":1},{"text":"But just without GERA, he's a political appointment or whatever it is, so he's not within ADEA.","start":1945.038,"stop":1952.444,"duration":7.41},{"text":"That's what I think this is about.","start":1952.444,"stop":1954.06,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, Your Honor.","start":1954.06,"stop":1954.56,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct.","start":1954.56,"stop":1955.21,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1955.21,"stop":1955.662,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"And you agree with that.","start":1955.662,"stop":1956.479,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1956.479,"stop":1956.896,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":1956.896,"stop":1957.712,"duration":0.82},{"text":"Then thank you very much.","start":1957.712,"stop":1959.281,"duration":1.57},{"text":"And then my argument comes into play that we shouldn't be deciding issues of an advisory nature that do not involve individuals who fall within the statute that someone once interpreted.","start":1959.281,"stop":1970.922,"duration":11.64}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you also agree that he is covered by GERA?","start":1970.922,"stop":1973.523,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"It is unclear, Your Honor.","start":1973.523,"stop":1976.059,"duration":2.54},{"text":"We don't -- GERA is unclear whether, first of all, in the Alaska case v. EEOC, whether it applies to States.","start":1976.059,"stop":1983.896,"duration":7.84},{"text":"States have argued that they're not included in the definition -- definition of GERA.","start":1983.896,"stop":1987.867,"duration":3.97},{"text":"And the State of Illinois has not waived sovereign immunity under the GERA statute.","start":1987.867,"stop":1997.139,"duration":9.27}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So what--","start":1997.139,"stop":1998.006,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"So whether or not there's a remedy there is very unclear.","start":1998.006,"stop":2000.275,"duration":2.27},{"text":"And this -- as Justice Breyer mentioned, it's been never discussed in this case.","start":2000.275,"stop":2008.045,"duration":7.77},{"text":"It was never discussed in the Seventh Circuit, never discussed in the district court.","start":2008.045,"stop":2012.333,"duration":4.29},{"text":"It wasn't discussed at the EEOC.","start":2012.333,"stop":2014.183,"duration":1.85},{"text":"When we filed a charge, the Attorney General didn't come in and say this should be handled under GERA.","start":2014.183,"stop":2019.152,"duration":4.97}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it was never discussed because you never raised it; isn't that right?","start":2019.152,"stop":2021.354,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Our position was it was inapplicable.","start":2021.354,"stop":2025.056,"duration":3.7},{"text":"We didn't -- we wouldn't raise it.","start":2025.056,"stop":2027.175,"duration":2.12},{"text":"It would be -- someone else would raise it.","start":2027.175,"stop":2029.025,"duration":1.85},{"text":"There's about a handful of cases nationally that are filed under GERA every year.","start":2029.025,"stop":2033.162,"duration":4.14},{"text":"Some years, there's no cases filed at the EEOC.","start":2033.162,"stop":2036.031,"duration":2.87},{"text":"It's seldom used.","start":2036.031,"stop":2037.314,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--You want us to hold that the Seventh Circuit lacked jurisdiction to consider whether there is a cause of action under Section 1983.","start":2037.314,"stop":2047.436,"duration":10.12},{"text":"So that precedent, that Seventh Circuit precedent, would be wedged from the books.","start":2047.436,"stop":2052.49,"duration":5.05},{"text":"The issue would be back in the case.","start":2052.49,"stop":2053.99,"duration":1.5},{"text":"If ultimately there was another appeal, maybe it would go to a different Seventh Circuit panel.","start":2053.99,"stop":2058.91,"duration":4.92},{"text":"Maybe it would come out differently.","start":2058.91,"stop":2060.227,"duration":1.32},{"text":"So you want that wiped away.","start":2060.227,"stop":2062.545,"duration":2.32},{"text":"And you want us to hold only -- to limit our consideration to the ADEA and not consider GERA, so that would be back in the case when it came -- when it went back to the district court.","start":2062.545,"stop":2074.603,"duration":12.06},{"text":"So that's correct?","start":2074.603,"stop":2075.253,"duration":0.65},{"text":"That's what you want?","start":2075.253,"stop":2076.539,"duration":1.29}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2076.539,"stop":2077.922,"duration":1.38},{"text":"And that's -- our position is we didn't argue the jurisdictional issue in our brief, but the court was concerned about it and we did address it in the Seventh Circuit.","start":2077.922,"stop":2087.078,"duration":9.16},{"text":"I would point out, in the Seventh Circuit's decision, though, their decision throughout the -- for instance, the -- the Seventh Circuit talks about Mr. Levin not being an appointee on the policymaking level and exempt, so that was in the case.","start":2087.078,"stop":2106.808,"duration":19.73},{"text":"It wasn't something where they just decided whether the ADEA precludes individuals that are covered.","start":2106.808,"stop":2114.814,"duration":8.01}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--And as far as the -- the preclusion is concerned, why does it make a difference whether it's ADEA or GERA?","start":2114.814,"stop":2125.872,"duration":11.06},{"text":"Wouldn't the arguable preclusion be even stronger under -- under GERA, because there is a special administrative remedy, you have to go to the EEOC first, and the only form for review is the Federal Circuit.","start":2125.872,"stop":2143.081,"duration":17.21}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"That's correct, Your Honor.","start":2143.081,"stop":2145.016,"duration":1.93},{"text":"The -- there's no preclusion under GERA or the ADEA.","start":2145.016,"stop":2150.253,"duration":5.24},{"text":"We've set forth that the Court should look at preclusion with two questions: The first question under preclusion is under Sea Clammers.","start":2150.253,"stop":2161.142,"duration":10.89},{"text":"Sea Clammers was a case where they passed a new statute with the new right and had an enforcement provision in the statute, and the issue was whether or not under Sea Clammers the Congress intended to preclude 1983 to enforce that statute.","start":2161.142,"stop":2182.807,"duration":21.66},{"text":"And the Court came to the conclusion, yes, that it would be inconsistent to use 1983 with that statute.","start":2182.807,"stop":2188.878,"duration":6.07},{"text":"The second standard that the Court has used is under Smith v. Fitzgerald, which is applicable here, if we're looking at whether the ADEA precludes somebody covered by the ADEA.","start":2188.878,"stop":2202.302,"duration":13.42},{"text":"And that is, when a statute is passed with an enforcement provision, did Congress intend to use that enforcement provision to also enforce preexisting independent statutory or constitutional rights?","start":2202.302,"stop":2218.747,"duration":16.44},{"text":"And, two, did Congress intend to use this provision in the new statute to be the sole exclusive remedy of the preexisting independent constitutional right?","start":2218.747,"stop":2235.273,"duration":16.53},{"text":"GERA cannot preclude a constitutional -- GERA -- there's no evidence that when Congress passed GERA they intended GERA to enforce the constitutional right to equal protection of the law.","start":2235.273,"stop":2252.401,"duration":17.13},{"text":"It doesn't--","start":2252.401,"stop":2252.968,"duration":0.57}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you a question about the constitutional right?","start":2252.968,"stop":2255.003,"duration":2.04},{"text":"Do you agree that the standard for an equal protection age-discrimination claim is traditional, full-blown, rational-basis review?","start":2255.003,"stop":2265.794,"duration":10.79}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, Your Honor.","start":2265.794,"stop":2266.628,"duration":0.83}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So that if there's any conceivable ground on which the decisionmaker could have decided that age was -- it was proper to make an age classification, there is no constitutional violation?","start":2266.628,"stop":2280.738,"duration":14.11}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"We can see where the rational basis test -- the court found we survived summary judgment on our equal protection gender discrimination claim and the age discrimination claim.","start":2280.738,"stop":2291.694,"duration":10.96}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm just talking about equal protection age discrimination.","start":2291.694,"stop":2294.478,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2294.478,"stop":2294.897,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And what if the Illinois legislature passed a statute that said: Now, forget about the ADEA.","start":2294.897,"stop":2301.134,"duration":6.24},{"text":"There is no ADEA.","start":2301.134,"stop":2302.401,"duration":1.27},{"text":"There is no state anti-discrimination law involved here.","start":2302.401,"stop":2306.386,"duration":3.99},{"text":"All we are talking about is equal protection.","start":2306.386,"stop":2307.971,"duration":1.59},{"text":"And they passed a law that said: All attorneys working for the State of Illinois must retire at the age of 60, because everybody knows, you know, once a lawyer passes 60, there's nothing left.","start":2307.971,"stop":2324.081,"duration":16.11}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"We're all in trouble.","start":2324.081,"stop":2326.2,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would that be -- would that survive a rational basis review?","start":2326.2,"stop":2332.004,"duration":5.8}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't believe so.","start":2332.004,"stop":2335.388,"duration":3.38},{"text":"This Court has considered that issue on two occasions.","start":2335.388,"stop":2340.609,"duration":5.22},{"text":"In Gregory v. Ashcroft that was before the Court.","start":2340.609,"stop":2344.828,"duration":4.22},{"text":"It was a -- the plaintiffs were excluded, like Mr. Levin, and yet this Court acknowledged the equal protection 1983 claim.","start":2344.828,"stop":2356.136,"duration":11.31},{"text":"They didn't -- the reasons that were used in that case were insufficient to meet the rational basis test.","start":2356.136,"stop":2364.242,"duration":8.11}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Theobald, are there any cases out there in the universe of cases in which a person does not have an ADEA claim or a GERA claim, but has pressed a successful constitutional claim based on age discrimination?","start":2364.242,"stop":2380.417,"duration":16.17}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, GERA has never been -- there's one case on GERA that we could find.","start":2380.417,"stop":2386.573,"duration":6.16},{"text":"It's over a 20-year-old District Court of New York decision that said GERA can't preclude anything.","start":2386.573,"stop":2392.811,"duration":6.24},{"text":"So if we put GERA together with the ADEA, it's only been really one district court has addressed that issue.","start":2392.811,"stop":2399.315,"duration":6.5},{"text":"And--","start":2399.315,"stop":2399.981,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I guess the question is, what are the circumstances in which, given the very low standard or given -- given the very low rational basis standard, what are the circumstances in which you would have a viable constitutional claim but not a statutory claim?","start":2399.981,"stop":2418.209,"duration":18.23},{"text":"What would that case look like?","start":2418.209,"stop":2419.894,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--If you had a claim under 1983, it would also, I believe, violate the ADEA.","start":2419.894,"stop":2429.85,"duration":9.96},{"text":"If that -- if I -- if that's your question.","start":2429.85,"stop":2433.638,"duration":3.79}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Would there be any unfairness to the parties if this case were remanded to the court of appeals with instructions for it in turn to remand to the district court to see whether or not the GERA issue has been properly presented or waived and to consider that?","start":2433.638,"stop":2451.516,"duration":17.88},{"text":"Would there be--","start":2451.516,"stop":2453.016,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it would be--","start":2453.016,"stop":2453.6,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"--any unfairness to the parties in doing that?","start":2453.6,"stop":2455.234,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Be very unfair to us, Your Honor.","start":2455.234,"stop":2458.086,"duration":2.85},{"text":"We were scheduled to go to trial in May before the Court granted its cert. The case has been pending almost six years.","start":2458.086,"stop":2464.34,"duration":6.25},{"text":"And to raise this issue at this -- this issue in GERA was raised this year.","start":2464.34,"stop":2470.661,"duration":6.32},{"text":"It wasn't raised for six years.","start":2470.661,"stop":2473.546,"duration":2.88},{"text":"Never -- whenever it was part of this case.","start":2473.546,"stop":2475.465,"duration":1.92},{"text":"And I don't think that--","start":2475.465,"stop":2476.565,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"That argument -- that argument could be made in the district court.","start":2476.565,"stop":2479.683,"duration":3.12}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, for something that's as suspect as GERA whether it even applies, it's -- the State has not said it applies--","start":2479.683,"stop":2490.905,"duration":11.22}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"What about doing--","start":2490.905,"stop":2491.491,"duration":0.59}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--the State of Illinois.","start":2491.491,"stop":2492.124,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--What if the -- is there anything unfair about this?","start":2492.124,"stop":2494.776,"duration":2.65},{"text":"I think Justice Ginsburg wrote an opinion in -- I recall a Third Circuit case involving ERISA or some medical thing, and an issue came up that was quite relevant and nobody had really thought about it before or done much about it.","start":2494.776,"stop":2507.1,"duration":12.32},{"text":"And what she wrote, to my recollection, is: Well, we would like the advice of the lower court if they want to give it.","start":2507.1,"stop":2513.087,"duration":5.99},{"text":"And so we send it back for the Third Circuit to consider whether it's appropriate to reach the issue, and if it is appropriate to reach the issue, do so.","start":2513.087,"stop":2523.962,"duration":10.88},{"text":"Or if they think the district court should reach it, do so.","start":2523.962,"stop":2526.778,"duration":2.82},{"text":"In other words, we can't figure it out at this moment what's fair in terms of the entire litigation.","start":2526.778,"stop":2532.166,"duration":5.39},{"text":"Now, would that -- would that be a serious problem for you or your client?","start":2532.166,"stop":2536.953,"duration":4.79}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, our position is that, yes, that none of these apply.","start":2536.953,"stop":2542.773,"duration":5.82},{"text":"ADEA cannot preclude somebody that's covered.","start":2542.773,"stop":2545.558,"duration":2.78},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit opinion covers that.","start":2545.558,"stop":2548.01,"duration":2.45},{"text":"The ADEA can't preclude somebody that's not covered.","start":2548.01,"stop":2551.362,"duration":3.35},{"text":"And this Court's opinion in Davis v. Passman and footnote 22 in Smith v. Robinson talks about--","start":2551.362,"stop":2562.001,"duration":10.64}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't know if you've satisfied my colleagues.","start":2562.001,"stop":2564.203,"duration":2.2},{"text":"I'm not sure that you've answered directly.","start":2564.203,"stop":2566.722,"duration":2.52},{"text":"I think your adversary is right that the Seventh Circuit held that no one is precluded from a 1983 claim, whether they're an employee or a non-employee.","start":2566.722,"stop":2581.565,"duration":14.84},{"text":"That's the way the case was litigated.","start":2581.565,"stop":2584.016,"duration":2.45},{"text":"That's the way they decided.","start":2584.016,"stop":2585.533,"duration":1.52},{"text":"The broad statement, whether he's an employee or not an employee, he doesn't have a 1983 -- he has a 1983 action.","start":2585.533,"stop":2595.241,"duration":9.71},{"text":"You've come in and you've said he's not an employee, so he's entitled to his 1983 claim.","start":2595.241,"stop":2605.197,"duration":9.96}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":2605.197,"stop":2606.616,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2606.616,"stop":2607.199,"duration":0.58},{"text":"My colleagues are asking you, that only takes care of half of this problem, because the circuit said even if he was an employee he would still have it.","start":2607.199,"stop":2618.424,"duration":11.22},{"text":"And so you're being asked, are you giving up that part of the claim, that he's not an employee?","start":2618.424,"stop":2625.16,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, he's been excluded.","start":2625.16,"stop":2627.612,"duration":2.45},{"text":"I--","start":2627.612,"stop":2630.029,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, then I assume -- if you're saying the qualified immunity ruling should not be reviewed because this person was not an employee, but instead covered by GERA, right?","start":2630.029,"stop":2642.705,"duration":12.68}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--We don't agree that he's covered by GERA, but it's -- it's not clear.","start":2642.705,"stop":2647.173,"duration":4.47}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, they didn't address GERA in the preclusion ruling, right?","start":2647.173,"stop":2651.059,"duration":3.89},{"text":"So presumably, they get another -- they get a chance on an interlocutory appeal; the whole thing is -- qualified immunity is supposed to protect them from trial.","start":2651.059,"stop":2659.165,"duration":8.11},{"text":"And if you say the GERA issue wasn't -- wasn't considered, even though the Seventh Circuit's ruling was sweeping and didn't distinguish, well, they should have a chance to assert qualified immunity under that ground, I would think.","start":2659.165,"stop":2671.222,"duration":12.06}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don't think that would factor in, Your Honor, with the qualified immunity analysis.","start":2671.222,"stop":2675.859,"duration":4.64},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit held and the district court held that your decision in Kimel acknowledged equal protection 1983 claims, and that's the issue in qualified immunity.","start":2675.859,"stop":2687.167,"duration":11.31},{"text":"They have not asked this Court to review the qualified immunity aspect of the Seventh Circuit's decision.","start":2687.167,"stop":2694.171,"duration":7},{"text":"Just the preclusion part.","start":2694.171,"stop":2695.521,"duration":1.35}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's true, but is that the issue?","start":2695.521,"stop":2695.837,"duration":0.32},{"text":"Is that really the qualified immunity issue, whether irrational age discrimination violates equal protection?","start":2695.837,"stop":2702.458,"duration":6.62},{"text":"Or is the qualified immunity issue whether, on the facts here, an official could believe that there was no constitutional violation, reasonably believe there was no constitutional violation?","start":2702.458,"stop":2717.017,"duration":14.56},{"text":"Isn't the latter--","start":2717.017,"stop":2718.45,"duration":1.43}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"It's the latter, yes.","start":2718.45,"stop":2718.933,"duration":0.48}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Isn't the latter the real question.","start":2718.933,"stop":2720.099,"duration":1.17}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2720.099,"stop":2720.749,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, that's not what the district court held though, is it?","start":2720.749,"stop":2723.485,"duration":2.74}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"The district court did so hold, yes.","start":2723.485,"stop":2727.537,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought the district court simply held that an official should have realized that irrational age discrimination was a violation of the Constitution, not that an official should have realized that it was a violation of the Constitution to do what was alleged to have been done here.","start":2727.537,"stop":2749.985,"duration":22.45}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it answered both questions, really.","start":2749.985,"stop":2754.789,"duration":4.8},{"text":"I don't -- I don't see the difference.","start":2754.789,"stop":2757.408,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't see the difference between the two?","start":2757.408,"stop":2759.824,"duration":2.42}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":2759.824,"stop":2760.926,"duration":1.1},{"text":"I -- I think that the court's -- the district court's decision held no qualified immunity.","start":2760.926,"stop":2766.012,"duration":5.09},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit cited this Court's decision in Kimel.","start":2766.012,"stop":2770.216,"duration":4.2},{"text":"The other cases before this Court, Gregory v. Ashcroft, acknowledged an age discrimination case brought through 1983 and it was clearly established.","start":2770.216,"stop":2783.106,"duration":12.89},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit acknowledged the 1983 age discrimination equal protection claim in 1977 in Gault v. Garrison.","start":2783.106,"stop":2794.414,"duration":11.31},{"text":"This is a well-settled issue.","start":2794.414,"stop":2796.016,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"If there's a qualified immunity appeal on the question -- on the issue of whether, let's say, a search was an unreasonable search, would qualified immunity be denied on the ground that an official should realize that an unreasonable search is unconstitutional?","start":2796.016,"stop":2814.311,"duration":18.3},{"text":"Would that be -- would that be the issue under qualified immunity?","start":2814.311,"stop":2818.197,"duration":3.89}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if the facts that the officer was presented, if there wasn't -- it wasn't well settled that the conduct--","start":2818.197,"stop":2825.785,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Ah, on the facts that were presented.","start":2825.785,"stop":2828.57,"duration":2.79}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes, Your Honor.","start":2828.57,"stop":2829.787,"duration":1.22},{"text":"So on the people that aren't covered, we have four groups: People that are under 40 under the ADEA; people in the -- that are exempt; individuals that work for a government employer that have less than 20 employees are not covered by the ADEA; and people that have a particular type of claim, a retaliation claim, a claim for emotional distress damages, something like that, they're not covered.","start":2829.787,"stop":2864.677,"duration":34.89},{"text":"The State concedes that the people under 40, they're going to bring equal protection claims through 1983.","start":2864.677,"stop":2874.299,"duration":9.62},{"text":"There's no difference between those people and Mr. Levin and the other two categories.","start":2874.299,"stop":2879.52,"duration":5.22},{"text":"You're either in or you're out.","start":2879.52,"stop":2881.289,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Yeah, but that's not what the Seventh Circuit held.","start":2881.289,"stop":2885.257,"duration":3.97},{"text":"I mean, that -- that may well be, but we're asked to review a holding by the Seventh Circuit that even if you aren't covered, even if you're not exempt, you still have a 1983 claim.","start":2885.257,"stop":2899.767,"duration":14.51},{"text":"That's -- that's why we took this case.","start":2899.767,"stop":2902.535,"duration":2.77},{"text":"And now you're -- you're telling us we should not review what the Seventh Circuit held.","start":2902.535,"stop":2909.622,"duration":7.09},{"text":"And that would presumably remain the circuit law, right?","start":2909.622,"stop":2913.76,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":2913.76,"stop":2915.393,"duration":1.63}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, not if there's no jurisdiction, right?","start":2915.393,"stop":2917.878,"duration":2.49},{"text":"If they didn't have jurisdiction, the thing would be wiped out.","start":2917.878,"stop":2920.93,"duration":3.05}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, that -- that is true.","start":2920.93,"stop":2924.382,"duration":3.45},{"text":"But I believe the Seventh Circuit in its opinion, and I could just refer to things in the appendix at page 57A.","start":2924.382,"stop":2931.972,"duration":7.59},{"text":"In the district court's opinion, the district court said Mr. Levin is exempt.","start":2931.972,"stop":2935.524,"duration":3.55},{"text":"In the Seventh Circuit opinion, the Seventh Circuit Docket No. 44 talks about end-runs.","start":2935.524,"stop":2951.449,"duration":15.93},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit Docket No. 37, page 67, the plaintiff was an employee on the policymaking level.","start":2951.449,"stop":2962.841,"duration":11.39},{"text":"So it's clear that the Seventh Circuit knew we argued that he was exempt.","start":2962.841,"stop":2973.382,"duration":10.54},{"text":"We argued that the -- being exempt under the district court's decision in Fitzgerald gives an individual the right to bring an equal protection claim.","start":2973.382,"stop":2986.139,"duration":12.76},{"text":"And the Court mentioned that in Fitzgerald, the decision in 2009, being exempt from Title IX.","start":2986.139,"stop":2992.876,"duration":6.74}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"In the Seventh Circuit, even though they -- you had that reference to him being exempt, the Seventh Circuit basically said it didn't make a difference, right?","start":2992.876,"stop":2998.864,"duration":5.99},{"text":"Whether he was covered as -- as an employee or not covered or covered under GERA or anything else, under their analysis, it doesn't make a difference.","start":2998.864,"stop":3007.203,"duration":8.34}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"I think we could read the opinion that way, but they certainly were aware that Mr. Levin was not covered.","start":3007.203,"stop":3013.89,"duration":6.69},{"text":"The -- the State has argued since Mr. Levin has been excluded before the Seventh Circuit and before this Court, they used the terms “ exhaustion ”, “ not exhausting remedies ”, and they used the word “ avoids the scheme ”, “ they avoid the ADEA ”.","start":3013.89,"stop":3031.085,"duration":17.2},{"text":"In the opening brief before -- the merits brief before this Court, the State used the term “ exhaustion ” or “ failure to exhaust ” more than a dozen times.","start":3031.085,"stop":3040.274,"duration":9.19},{"text":"They used the term “ avoiding the ADEA ” at least six times.","start":3040.274,"stop":3046.597,"duration":6.32},{"text":"This argument is the old Zombro argument, the first case that held preclusion where somebody didn't go through.","start":3046.597,"stop":3054.367,"duration":7.77},{"text":"Exhaustion has nothing to do with this case.","start":3054.367,"stop":3057.986,"duration":3.62},{"text":"This Court's opinion in Patsy v. Board of Regents said you don't have to exhaust from 1983.","start":3057.986,"stop":3063.807,"duration":5.82},{"text":"All the cases, Johnson v. Railway Express, CBOCS v. Humphries, there's no exhaustion required.","start":3063.807,"stop":3073.33,"duration":9.52},{"text":"And to top it off, Mr. Levin, he exhausted his remedies.","start":3073.33,"stop":3079.484,"duration":6.15},{"text":"He filed at the EEOC.","start":3079.484,"stop":3081.268,"duration":1.78},{"text":"He got a right to sue under Title VII.","start":3081.268,"stop":3083.97,"duration":2.7},{"text":"So--","start":3083.97,"stop":3084.72,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Let's assume that the question that was presented is before us.","start":3084.72,"stop":3089.174,"duration":4.45},{"text":"And you -- you have argued Fitzgerald.","start":3089.174,"stop":3091.892,"duration":2.72},{"text":"The other side says Smith v. Robinson should control.","start":3091.892,"stop":3095.028,"duration":3.14},{"text":"So why shouldn't the Handicapped Act decision control?","start":3095.028,"stop":3100.165,"duration":5.14},{"text":"That, like the ADEA, has allowed procedural parts that wouldn't be included in an equal protection claim.","start":3100.165,"stop":3112.472,"duration":12.31}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--We believe, Your Honor, that those two cases are the second standard.","start":3112.472,"stop":3117.357,"duration":4.88},{"text":"The Smith -- we agree with the standard in Smith.","start":3117.357,"stop":3120.575,"duration":3.22},{"text":"We agree in the standard with Fitzgerald.","start":3120.575,"stop":3122.859,"duration":2.28},{"text":"And the standard in Smith, what that case was about was the Educational for All Handicapped Act, whether that Act precluded the use of 504 of the Rehabilitation Act, the statutory claim, and whether it precluded 1983 constitutional claims.","start":3122.859,"stop":3140.303,"duration":17.44},{"text":"And the Court in Smith v. Fitzgerald said that it did, because there was no -- the EHA, the remedies and the procedures there was not for a de novo review in court.","start":3140.303,"stop":3152.946,"duration":12.64},{"text":"So the plaintiff's claim was precluded.","start":3152.946,"stop":3156.648,"duration":3.7},{"text":"We have no problem with the Smith standard.","start":3156.648,"stop":3158.684,"duration":2.04},{"text":"But the Court also said in Smith that if there are matters that are offered to the children, the disability of the disabled children or their parents under the EHA that that doesn't cover, those things, if they're offered to parents and if they're offered in a discriminatory matter or denied for discrimination, those claims can be brought under the 1983 equal protection claims or under Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act, the preexisting statutory claim.","start":3158.684,"stop":3193.188,"duration":34.5},{"text":"So applying that to the ADA, there is no evidence that in passing the ADA for covered individuals that Congress intended to preclude the preexisting 1983 equal protection claim.","start":3193.188,"stop":3210.133,"duration":16.94},{"text":"So our second standard in our brief is the Smith-Fitzgerald standard.","start":3210.133,"stop":3215.771,"duration":5.64},{"text":"In Fitzgerald, the Court went further and explained if the rights and protections of the statute that is seeking precluding are different than the equal protection claim, then there is no preclusion.","start":3215.771,"stop":3230.713,"duration":14.94},{"text":"And here, the rights and protections between the ADA and the equal protection through 1983 are vast, are vast.","start":3230.713,"stop":3239.986,"duration":9.27},{"text":"There's different parties, different defendants.","start":3239.986,"stop":3242.771,"duration":2.79},{"text":"In the ADEA the entity is the defendant.","start":3242.771,"stop":3245.64,"duration":2.87},{"text":"In equal protection 1983 it's individual.","start":3245.64,"stop":3249.092,"duration":3.45},{"text":"In the ADEA, all these exemptions of people that aren't covered; if somebody pursues a 1983 equal protection claim, there is no exemptions of individuals.","start":3249.092,"stop":3261.666,"duration":12.57},{"text":"So to conclude, Your Honor, we adopt the Smith standard.","start":3261.666,"stop":3270.005,"duration":8.34},{"text":"We have no problem with Smith.","start":3270.005,"stop":3271.123,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, I'm trying to -- trying to see how -- how many of these arguments that you have made before us about why -- why we can't get to the holding of the Seventh Circuit, how many of them you made in your brief in opposition.","start":3271.123,"stop":3294.054,"duration":22.93},{"text":"I mean, we -- we don't like to dismiss a case as improvidently granted, and--","start":3294.054,"stop":3299.958,"duration":5.9}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"We could have done--","start":3299.958,"stop":3302.477,"duration":2.52}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--only when the -- when the case is before us, counsel suddenly finds all sorts of reasons why we shouldn't have taken it in the first place.","start":3302.477,"stop":3309.915,"duration":7.44},{"text":"You should have told us that before we took it.","start":3309.915,"stop":3313.284,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"--We could have done a better job -- we could have done a better job, Your Honor, and I apologize for that.","start":3313.284,"stop":3316.736,"duration":3.45},{"text":"We did try to point out that Mr. Levin was exempt.","start":3316.736,"stop":3319.938,"duration":3.2},{"text":"We did say that and how under Fitzgerald the exemptions formed the basis of an equal protection claim.","start":3319.938,"stop":3325.756,"duration":5.82}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I read your brief in opposition as -- as going exclusively to what your unfortunate brother barely had a chance to argue; that is, the merits of the case.","start":3325.756,"stop":3338.233,"duration":12.48},{"text":"That -- that's what your brief in opposition addressed, and here we end up spending most of our discussion on -- on other stuff.","start":3338.233,"stop":3346.253,"duration":8.02},{"text":"I don't -- I don't like to encourage that.","start":3346.253,"stop":3348.521,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Edward R. Theobald III","textObjs":[{"text":"We could have done a better job.","start":3348.521,"stop":3351.573,"duration":3.05},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3351.573,"stop":3352.489,"duration":0.92}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3352.489,"stop":3353.156,"duration":0.67},{"text":"Mr. Scodro, you have five minutes remaining.","start":3353.156,"stop":3355.708,"duration":2.55}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3355.708,"stop":3357.893,"duration":2.18},{"text":"Just a couple of quick points.","start":3357.893,"stop":3359.26,"duration":1.37},{"text":"Justice Kagan, in answer to your question to my colleague, I am not aware of any cases, nor can I conceive of one, in which one would have an equal protection claim but could not state a cause of action under the ADEA.","start":3359.26,"stop":3372.084,"duration":12.82},{"text":"And I think this Court's decision in Kimel makes clear that such a universe does not exist.","start":3372.084,"stop":3376.203,"duration":4.12},{"text":"The question in response to a question from Justice Sotomayor regarding the scope of the Seventh Circuit's decision below, proof positive that the Seventh Circuit was -- was, in fact, announcing the sweeping rule that Respondent sought is the fact that the court departs openly from the -- the law in other circuits.","start":3376.203,"stop":3395.866,"duration":19.66},{"text":"So it was in fact they were creating, they were knowingly creating the split.","start":3395.866,"stop":3399.485,"duration":3.62},{"text":"The only reference in the analysis portion of the case to the fact that there are exemptions for high-level officials appears on page 33A.","start":3399.485,"stop":3408.441,"duration":8.96}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you tell me what the authority is for Congress to extinguish a right for a constitutional violation?","start":3408.441,"stop":3420.581,"duration":12.14},{"text":"Meaning--","start":3420.581,"stop":3421.898,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure.","start":3421.898,"stop":3422.564,"duration":0.67}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--assume that someone -- it was the question that Justice Alito asked you -- someone under of the age of 40, someone who's not covered by any statute, someone who's part of an employer under 20.","start":3422.564,"stop":3435.989,"duration":13.43},{"text":"What would suggest to you in this statute that Congress intended to extinguish those people's rights?","start":3435.989,"stop":3445.095,"duration":9.11}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Sure, Your Honor.","start":3445.095,"stop":3445.68,"duration":0.59},{"text":"There are really two parts to my answer.","start":3445.68,"stop":3447.247,"duration":1.57},{"text":"The first is they -- they didn't.","start":3447.247,"stop":3449.232,"duration":1.99},{"text":"It has been overstated what has not -- what has been exempted.","start":3449.232,"stop":3452.434,"duration":3.2},{"text":"Our position is that nobody whose Section 1983 claims are -- would be displaced would not, in exchange, receive the full rights and benefits under the ADEA.","start":3452.434,"stop":3464.408,"duration":11.97},{"text":"There is a reference to--","start":3464.408,"stop":3466.008,"duration":1.6}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":3466.008,"stop":3466.593,"duration":0.59},{"text":"Restate that again so I understand what you are saying.","start":3466.593,"stop":3468.693,"duration":2.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Of course.","start":3468.693,"stop":3469.027,"duration":0.33},{"text":"Nobody who -- the universe of -- of employees, or workers, to use the neutral term here.","start":3469.027,"stop":3475.799,"duration":6.77},{"text":"The universe of workers who would not have a Section 1983 claim under the State's theory, that every member of that universe would have a right to bring a claim under the Equal Protection Clause.","start":3475.799,"stop":3488.941,"duration":13.14},{"text":"The under 40s, we agree -- as we say in our brief, we agree that under 40 that was not the social ill that Congress was addressing in the Age Discrimination Act, consistent with this Court's holding in Cline; and, therefore, those individuals retain their right, the small workplace, the under 20.","start":3488.941,"stop":3507.587,"duration":18.65},{"text":"The EEOC--","start":3507.587,"stop":3508.837,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Absent the GERA--","start":3508.837,"stop":3510.789,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":3510.789,"stop":3511.439,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--would people who are executive officers, etcetera, absent the GERA--","start":3511.439,"stop":3519.995,"duration":8.56}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":3519.995,"stop":3520.161,"duration":0.17}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--would they have retained their constitutional right?","start":3520.161,"stop":3522.311,"duration":2.15}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"They would.","start":3522.311,"stop":3522.727,"duration":0.42},{"text":"We do not -- we -- we understand the displacement doctrine and -- and certainly, as applied here, it would displace the 1983 remedies.","start":3522.727,"stop":3530.148,"duration":7.42},{"text":"We assume that courts retain their inherent authority to use equitable power to stop the ongoing violation of the Constitution.","start":3530.148,"stop":3537.154,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Scodro, you are in a situation where the question is not whether the remedial scheme displaces a 1983 suit brought for a violation of the same statute that contains the remedial scheme.","start":3537.154,"stop":3549.378,"duration":12.22},{"text":"Instead, you have to argue that this remedial scheme displaces a preexisting statutory or constitutional right.","start":3549.378,"stop":3557.132,"duration":7.75},{"text":"And when we've had that situation in the past, we've looked to more than just the remedial scheme itself.","start":3557.132,"stop":3563.721,"duration":6.59},{"text":"You know, Smith looks to the language of the statute, which refers to constitutional claims.","start":3563.721,"stop":3569.373,"duration":5.65},{"text":"It looks for legislative history.","start":3569.373,"stop":3571.392,"duration":2.02},{"text":"It looks to the coincidence between the statute -- the new statutory claim and the old constitutional claim.","start":3571.392,"stop":3578.398,"duration":7.01},{"text":"And it seems to me that you don't have any of those things.","start":3578.398,"stop":3581.231,"duration":2.83},{"text":"All you have is a complicated remedial scheme, which would be enough to say, look, you can't bring 1983 suits to vindicate this statute.","start":3581.231,"stop":3592.821,"duration":11.59},{"text":"But seems as though it's not enough under our case law to repeal preexisting rights and remedies.","start":3592.821,"stop":3600.494,"duration":7.67}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, Smith -- as we understand Smith, and certainly as it's been read by Rancho Palos Verdes in Fitzgerald even, it stands for the proposition that the lodestar inquiry and I think word primary emphasis of that phrase may be used in Fitzgerald to describe the comprehensiveness of the regime as the first and most important inquiry.","start":3600.494,"stop":3619.808,"duration":19.31},{"text":"After that, Smith makes clear that we are allowed to consider if there is a comprehensive regime, whether there is contrary evidence in the face of the legislative history, as there is, for example, for Title VII, not so for the ADEA.","start":3619.808,"stop":3632.298,"duration":12.49}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But are we -- if the ADEA is expanding the Civil Rights protection against age discrimination much more generous to the employee, isn't it strange to think that Congress at the same time wanted employees to have these expanded rights and to do away with the preexisting remedies?","start":3632.298,"stop":3655.914,"duration":23.62}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, not at all.","start":3655.914,"stop":3658.1,"duration":2.19},{"text":"When Congress provided the expanded right, they recognized that there were characteristics particular to age discrimination that warranted very low damages awards and a procedural predicate that would emphasize swift and informal dispute resolution.","start":3658.1,"stop":3671.84,"duration":13.74}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3671.84,"stop":3672.94,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you.","start":3672.94,"stop":3673.356,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3673.356,"stop":3674.39,"duration":1.03}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Oct 7, 2013","petitioner":"Lisa Madigan et al.","respondent":"Harvey N. Levin","docket":"12-872","citation":"571 US _ (2013)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/571/12-872","lowerCourt":"","grantedOn":"Mar 18, 2013","decidedOn":"Oct 15, 2013"}